5
00:01:01,603 --> 00:01:03,188
and we never finished.

6
00:01:03,188 --> 00:01:04,523
I thought if you're free,
we could try it again.

7
00:01:04,523 --> 00:01:06,233
‐ That'd be irresponsible!

8
00:01:06,233 --> 00:01:09,152
IZAYA: The Dollars don't expect
you to take responsibility.

9
00:01:09,152 --> 00:01:10,237
‐ It's gonna be okay.

10
00:01:10,237 --> 00:01:11,530
She's sleeping soundly now.

11
00:01:11,530 --> 00:01:14,032
VARONA: [shouting in Russian]

12
00:01:14,032 --> 00:01:16,201
It appears the bike
was marked somehow.

13
00:01:16,201 --> 00:01:19,454
Or perhaps we can use it
as a lure for an ambush.

14
00:01:19,454 --> 00:01:26,461
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15
00:01:56,658 --> 00:01:59,870
MASAOMI: I'm about to tell you
the tale of a worthless guy.

16
00:02:01,747 --> 00:02:03,915
It was exactly like
you told me, Izaya.

17
00:02:03,915 --> 00:02:07,002
What?
Oh, right.

18
00:02:09,713 --> 00:02:13,133
A high‐school dropout who
ran away from both his home

19
00:02:13,133 --> 00:02:14,676
and from school.

20
00:02:14,676 --> 00:02:17,763
<i>[low‐key piano music]</i>

21
00:02:17,763 --> 00:02:19,473
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22
00:02:19,473 --> 00:02:21,933
‐ Bullet trains sure are
amazing, aren't they?

23
00:02:21,933 --> 00:02:23,769
‐ What do you think is
so amazing about 'em?

24
00:02:23,769 --> 00:02:26,438
‐ The fact that they
go so straight.

25
00:02:26,438 --> 00:02:29,191
‐ You're still as much
of a weirdo as ever, Saki.

26
00:02:29,191 --> 00:02:32,736
SAKI: Am I?
I don't think I'm as bad as you.

27
00:02:32,736 --> 00:02:34,446
‐ Am I really that weird?

28
00:02:34,446 --> 00:02:35,781
‐ Yeah.

29
00:02:35,781 --> 00:02:37,949
I know that you hate Izaya's
guts and all,

30
00:02:37,949 --> 00:02:40,869
and yet you're running around
as his gofer.

31
00:02:40,869 --> 00:02:42,621
It's totally twisted,

32
00:02:42,621 --> 00:02:44,414
like some subway map.

33
00:02:44,414 --> 00:02:46,792
Although I actually like that
about you.

34
00:02:47,959 --> 00:02:49,503
‐ Uh...

35
00:02:49,503 --> 00:02:53,131
You don't pull your punches when
it comes to sensitive stuff.

36
00:02:53,131 --> 00:02:55,300
He doesn't have any way
to support himself,

37
00:02:55,300 --> 00:02:56,760
so he's making ends meet

38
00:02:56,760 --> 00:02:59,388
by being that
good‐for‐nothing's gofer.

39
00:02:59,388 --> 00:03:01,807
He's a guy with
no real purpose‐‐

40
00:03:01,807 --> 00:03:04,351
a guy with nothing
to offer the world.

41
00:03:04,351 --> 00:03:08,438
<i>♪ ♪</i>

42
00:03:08,438 --> 00:03:10,357
‐ [grunting]

43
00:03:10,357 --> 00:03:13,026
[growling]

44
00:03:13,026 --> 00:03:14,903
That goddamn fleabag.

45
00:03:14,903 --> 00:03:17,906
He's wasting my time!

46
00:03:17,906 --> 00:03:20,367
[growling]

47
00:03:21,993 --> 00:03:25,831
MASAOMI: For some reason,
the guy still has a friend.

48
00:03:25,831 --> 00:03:27,874
‐ Having a good morning, Mikado?

49
00:03:27,874 --> 00:03:30,293
‐ Uh, Aoba, what's going on?

50
00:03:30,293 --> 00:03:33,088
I thought we were supposed
to meet at 11:00.

51
00:03:33,088 --> 00:03:34,339
‐ Yeah, I know.

52
00:03:34,339 --> 00:03:35,632
But before we go meet Anri,

53
00:03:35,632 --> 00:03:36,842
I had something important

54
00:03:36,842 --> 00:03:38,677
I wanted to talk
to you about first.

55
00:03:38,677 --> 00:03:41,263
‐ You could've just called my
cell if you wanted to talk.

56
00:03:41,263 --> 00:03:44,558
Uh, hey, who gave you
my address?

57
00:03:44,558 --> 00:03:46,685
‐ It's about the Dollars.
‐ Uh?

58
00:03:46,685 --> 00:03:49,104
‐ But not here.
Let's go somewhere else.

59
00:03:50,313 --> 00:03:52,023
‐ [stammering]

60
00:03:52,023 --> 00:03:53,859
‐ If you need a little time
to get changed,

61
00:03:53,859 --> 00:03:55,318
we don't mind waiting for you.

62
00:03:55,318 --> 00:03:56,987
‐ [exhales softly]

63
00:03:59,531 --> 00:04:02,200
I wonder if you can still
call them friends,

64
00:04:02,200 --> 00:04:04,578
even though you haven't
seen them for a long time.

65
00:04:04,578 --> 00:04:06,413
Good morning!

66
00:04:06,413 --> 00:04:07,664
Yay! Wait.

67
00:04:07,664 --> 00:04:09,082
Figures that no one's around.

68
00:04:09,082 --> 00:04:10,876
It's morning, after all.

69
00:04:10,876 --> 00:04:14,838
Plus, my last login was probably
about a week ago.

70
00:04:14,838 --> 00:04:17,382
I'm super sorry that I couldn't
be part of these chats

71
00:04:17,382 --> 00:04:19,050
for such a long time.

72
00:04:19,050 --> 00:04:21,511
Thanks to work, I've been
away with my girlfriend

73
00:04:21,511 --> 00:04:24,347
for a lovey‐dovey rendezvous
in Tohoku.

74
00:04:24,347 --> 00:04:26,224
How have you guys been?

75
00:04:26,224 --> 00:04:28,351
Guess I'll dig through the logs
and see what you did

76
00:04:28,351 --> 00:04:29,811
over the long weekend.

77
00:04:29,811 --> 00:04:33,190
Yeah!

78
00:04:33,190 --> 00:04:36,401
‐ I bet you're happy that you're
finally able to log on.

79
00:04:36,401 --> 00:04:38,862
You're such a slave
to the Internet, Masaomi.

80
00:04:38,862 --> 00:04:40,155
Masochist much?

81
00:04:40,155 --> 00:04:41,531
‐ What's that supposed to mean?

82
00:04:41,531 --> 00:04:43,909
‐ Well, you only meet up
with people online,

83
00:04:43,909 --> 00:04:46,161
even when you can
see them in person.

84
00:04:46,161 --> 00:04:48,371
‐ It's not that I won't see 'em.

85
00:04:48,371 --> 00:04:50,832
It's that I can't.

86
00:04:50,832 --> 00:04:52,751
Huh? What the...

87
00:04:52,751 --> 00:04:53,960
‐ You're weird.

88
00:04:53,960 --> 00:04:55,712
‐ What makes people friends

89
00:04:55,712 --> 00:04:58,298
